<TITLE> Khalilzad says will resign as US enovy at UN </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Kabul, April 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Afghan-born US ambassador to the United Nations, Zalmay Khalilzad, has said he will resign within months and again rejected suggestions he might run for president in his country of birth. Khalilzad is a former US ambassador in Afghanistan who earned the nickname the viceroy because of his influence when he served in Kabul from 2003 to 2005. At the time, Afghanistan was drafting a constitution and preparing for its first elections after the ouster of the Taliban in 2001. In an interview with Afghanistan's Ariana television station in New York, Khalilzad said he would quit as US envoy to the United Nations in "several months" and would begin "personal work". "I said it earlier too, I am not a candidate for any position in Afghanistan but am at the service of Afghanistan's people," Khalilzad said. In the comments broadcast by Ariana on Thursday, Khalilzad did not elaborate on what personal work he planned to do, or where he might do it. A spokesman in New York said on Wednesday Khalilzad he had no immediate plan to resign. Appointed by President George W Bush, Khalilzad's term at the United Nations is anyway likely to end early in 2009, when a new US president will take office. Khalilzad was born in Afghanistan and first went to the United States as an exchange student in 1966, attending high school in California. He has long been a US citizen. It was not clear if Khalilzad held Afghan citizenship. The Afghan constitution says candidates for president have to be Afghans and can not hold a second nationality. Last week, Western-backed Afghan President Hamid Karzai gave his strongest indication yet he would again stand for president in an election due next year. Khalilzad became US ambassador to Iraq after Afghanist
